  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through various mechanisms and frameworks:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Provide standardized guidelines for combating money laundering\n\n2. Legal Harmonization\n- Countries align national legislation with international standards\n- Establish consistent definitions and criminal provisions\n- Create uniform reporting and compliance requirements\n\n3. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Share financial intelligence and evidence across borders\n- Extradition agreements for money laundering offenses\n\n4. Regulatory Coordination\n- International financial institutions monitor cross-border transactions\n- Banks and financial institutions implement global compliance protocols\n- Enhanced due diligence and know-your-customer regulations\n\n5. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) exchange data\n- Interpol and international law enforcement networks\n- Real-time tracking of suspicious financial activities\n\n6. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Coordinated efforts to disrupt money laundering networks\n- Penalties for financial institutions failing to meet international standards\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering.",
